/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/how-anthropics-contextual-retrieval-changes-rag-architecture/index.html:240:<p>I wrote about context decay in <a href="/blog/llm-context-windows-explained/">LLM Context Windows Explained</a>. The same idea shows up earlier in the pipeline. Small chunks improve recall because they are easier to match. Small chunks also strip away the frame that made the text identifiable.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/how-anthropics-contextual-retrieval-changes-rag-architecture/index.html:268:<p>My <a href="/blog/reranking-in-rag-why-your-top-k-results-are-probably-wrong/">reranking piece</a> makes the case that vector similarity is a decent filter and a weak ranker. Contextual Retrieval fixes something earlier. It makes the filter more likely to surface the right chunk at all.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/how-anthropics-contextual-retrieval-changes-rag-architecture/index.html:316:<p>I covered the same cost logic in <a href="/blog/prompt-caching-what-it-is-and-when-the-math-works/">Prompt Caching</a>. Anthropic's docs say prompt caching can cut latency by <strong>more than 2x</strong> and reduce costs by <strong>up to 90%</strong> in the right setup. Those numbers matter here because contextualization cost lands up front. Query-time retrieval does not change much unless I add reranking.</p>
