/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/token-counting-isnt-optional-a-practical-guide-to-llm-cost-control/index.html:194:      <a href="/blog/" class="back-link">← All posts</a>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/token-counting-isnt-optional-a-practical-guide-to-llm-cost-control/index.html:241:<p>Providers charge up to five times more for output tokens due to this autoregressive bottleneck. I always optimize my architectures for minimal output generation. You should aggressively instruct the model to be concise and return only the requested data points without conversational filler. You can explore techniques like <a href="/blog/speculative-decoding-explained/">Speculative Decoding</a> to understand how inference engines attempt to speed up this sequential generation process.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/token-counting-isnt-optional-a-practical-guide-to-llm-cost-control/index.html:267:<p>The solution requires strict filtering before the prompt is assembled. You must evaluate the relevance of every single chunk. I highly recommend implementing a cross-encoder to score and filter your vector search results, a technique I cover extensively in my post on <a href="/blog/reranking-in-rag-why-your-top-k-results-are-probably-wrong/">Reranking in RAG</a>. You should also look into <a href="/blog/prompt-caching-what-it-is-and-when-the-math-works/">Prompt Caching</a> to offset the costs when you are forced to send massive system instructions repeatedly.</p>
