/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:31:  <meta property="og:url"         content="https://ninadpathak.com/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/">
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:42:  <link rel="canonical" href="https://ninadpathak.com/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/">
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:95:    "@id": "https://ninadpathak.com/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/"
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:114:      "item": "https://ninadpathak.com/blog/"
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:120:      "item": "https://ninadpathak.com/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/"
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:137:      <li><a href="/blog/"      class="nav-link active">Writing</a></li>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:166:    <a href="/blog/"      class="mobile-nav-link">Writing</a>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:184:      <li class="breadcrumb-item"><a href="/blog/">Blog</a></li>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:194:      <a href="/blog/" class="back-link">← All posts</a>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:241:<p>Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF) avoids the normalization problem entirely. RRF scores each document by summing <code>1 / (k + rank)</code> across all result lists the document appears in, where <code>k=60</code> is a constant from <a href="https://opensearch.org/blog/introducing-reciprocal-rank-fusion-hybrid-search/">the original Cormack et al. SIGIR 2009 paper</a>. Rank position is all that matters; the underlying scores are discarded.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:243:<p>The practical advantage of RRF: no tuning required for initial deployment. The <code>k=60</code> constant generalizes well across domains. You don't need labeled data to set weights. <a href="https://www.elastic.co/search-labs/blog/improving-information-retrieval-elastic-stack-hybrid">Elasticsearch recommends RRF as the starting point</a> precisely because of this robustness.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:245:<p><a href="https://www.elastic.co/search-labs/blog/improving-information-retrieval-elastic-stack-hybrid">Elastic's benchmarks</a> show RRF increasing average NDCG@10 by 1.4% over their Learned Sparse Encoder alone and 18% over BM25 alone across the BEIR benchmark suite.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:246:<p><a href="https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/blog/azure-ai-foundry-blog/azure-ai-search-outperforming-vector-search-with-hybrid-retrieval-and-reranking/3929167">Azure AI Search benchmarks</a> show hybrid retrieval plus semantic reranking consistently outperforming pure vector search even with OpenAI's <code>text-embedding-3-large</code> as the dense retriever. The combination of hybrid search and a cross-encoder reranker on top produces the strongest results.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:248:<p><a href="https://weaviate.io/blog/search-mode-benchmarking">Weaviate's search mode benchmarking</a> compares pure keyword, pure vector, and hybrid across their own benchmarks and shows hybrid consistently at the top, though the margins vary.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:259:<p><strong>Elasticsearch</strong> supports hybrid search through the <code>sub_searches</code> + <code>rank</code> API. <a href="https://www.elastic.co/search-labs/blog/linear-retriever-hybrid-search">Elasticsearch's linear retriever</a> supports weighted linear combination as an alternative to RRF, which can outperform RRF once you have enough annotated queries to tune the weights. Their data suggests roughly 40 annotated queries is the threshold where tuned weights beat untuned RRF.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:263:<p>Linear combination with min-max normalization can outperform RRF when the score distributions are stable and you have labeled data for weight tuning. <a href="https://www.elastic.co/search-labs/blog/weighted-reciprocal-rank-fusion-rrf">Elasticsearch's benchmarks</a> found hybrid dismax with name boosting achieved a mean NDCG of 0.7497 versus RRF's 0.7068 on one e-commerce dataset, with the gap closing as document diversity increased.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:272:<p><a href="https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/blog/azure-ai-foundry-blog/azure-ai-search-outperforming-vector-search-with-hybrid-retrieval-and-reranking/3929167">Azure's benchmark data</a> shows the hybrid + rerank combination consistently outperforming hybrid alone by a significant margin. I wrote about reranking mechanics in depth at <a href="/blog/reranking-in-rag-why-your-top-k-results-are-probably-wrong/">Reranking in RAG</a>.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/hybrid-search-bm25-vector-search/index.html:277:<p>I covered embedding model selection in <a href="/blog/embedding-models-compared/">Embedding Models Compared</a>, which is relevant here: the dense retriever quality has a floor effect on hybrid search. A weak dense retriever won't be salvaged by BM25. The combination amplifies both retrievers' strengths, not their weaknesses.</p>
