/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/semantic-caching-rag-optimization/index.html:256:<p><a href="https://redis.io/blog/10-techniques-for-semantic-cache-optimization/">Redis LangCache documentation</a> recommends starting at 0.88 cosine similarity for an FAQ-style cache, then tuning down gradually as you observe false positive rates. A practical technique is confidence buffering: if your threshold is 0.90, only serve cache hits above 0.92. The buffer absorbs borderline cases without requiring you to tighten the primary threshold.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/semantic-caching-rag-optimization/index.html:258:<p><a href="https://redis.io/blog/10-techniques-for-semantic-cache-optimization/">Redis recommends domain partitioning</a> as an explicit technique: don't mix customer support queries with product documentation queries in the same cache namespace. Different domains have different similarity distributions, and a threshold calibrated for one domain will over-fire or under-fire on another.</p>
/Users/ninad/Development/NinadPathak/output/blog/semantic-caching-rag-optimization/index.html:284:<p>I covered retrieval improvements with <a href="/blog/how-anthropics-contextual-retrieval-changes-rag-architecture/">contextual retrieval here</a> and <a href="/blog/reranking-in-rag-why-your-top-k-results-are-probably-wrong/">reranking here</a>. Semantic caching fits in the layer above both.</p>
