+Generic tutorial advice usually collapses those two forms into the same template. That is how you get pages titled "Build your first webhook consumer" that open with six architecture paragraphs, three optional providers, and twelve branch points before the reader has run a single line of code. A beginner does not experience that as depth. A beginner experiences that as friction.
+
+My take is that a technical tutorial should feel slightly artificial on purpose. I want one operating system, one package manager, one SDK version, one directory structure, and one finished artifact. That constraint is not a weakness. That constraint is what makes learning possible. I can broaden the material later in a how-to guide or reference page.
+
+GitHub's docs make the same separation in their [content model for tutorials and quickstarts](https://docs.github.com/en/contributing/style-guide-and-content-model/content-models/tutorials-and-quickstarts). A tutorial there starts with audience, prerequisites, and the artifact the reader will build. That requirement sounds small, but it forces the writer to decide what the reader will know and what will exist at the end.
+
+## Narrow scope teaches better than broad coverage
+
+Google's [sample code guidance](https://developers.google.com/tech-writing/two/sample-code) says good samples should be correct, concise, understandable, reusable, and sequenced from simple to more complex. Learning-science research lands in the same place. The [worked-example effect](https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0963721420922183) shows that novices learn more from studying worked solutions than from solving equivalent problems cold, because unguided problem solving burns working-memory capacity on search rather than understanding.
+
+That point changes how I scope a tutorial. I do not try to "cover the product." I choose one skill with one visible win. Good tutorial scopes look like these:
+
+1. Build a webhook receiver that verifies signatures and logs accepted events.
+2. Add structured outputs to one extraction pipeline and validate the JSON schema.
+3. Create a CLI command that uploads one file and prints the resulting asset URL.
+
+Bad tutorial scopes usually contain silent curriculum inflation. "Build a RAG chatbot" often hides vector embeddings, chunking strategy, retrieval tuning, prompt design, streaming, and frontend state management inside one page. A reader may finish it by brute force. Very few readers will understand which part actually mattered.
+
+I have seen this problem repeatedly in client drafts. A team wants one flagship tutorial to introduce the product, answer every integration question, and rank for a broad keyword. That brief produces a page that teaches nothing well. If I need a tutorial that teaches, I cut the surface area until a first-time reader can keep the whole task in their head.
+
+## Every step needs a visible check
+
+A reader should never have to guess whether step 4 worked. Google recommends explaining how to run sample code, including dependencies, setup, and [expected output or results](https://developers.google.com/tech-writing/two/sample-code). That sentence should be obvious, yet a huge number of tutorials still omit expected output and force the reader to infer success from side effects.
+
+I write checkpoints into the body, not as an afterthought:
+
+1. Show the exact command.
+2. Show the exact file change.
+3. Show the exact output, log line, HTTP status, or UI element that confirms success.
+4. Name the failure mode that usually appears if the step goes wrong.
+
+That fourth point does more teaching than many long explanations. A line like "A `401 invalid signature` response usually means your local secret does not match the dashboard secret" gives the reader a diagnostic rule they can reuse later. A line like "If you do not see the uploaded asset URL in stdout, check that `OPENAI_API_KEY` is exported in the same shell session" teaches environment behavior, not just product behavior.
+
+Microsoft's [guidance for procedures and instructions](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/style-guide/procedures-instructions/writing-step-by-step-instructions) pushes writers toward clear prerequisites, imperative steps, and procedures short enough to stay cognitively manageable. I agree with that framing, though I think most teams still write steps that are too large. One numbered item should do one thing. "Install dependencies, create the app, configure secrets, and start the dev server" is four steps wearing one trench coat.
+
+## Explanations belong near the action they unlock
+
+Writers often dump all conceptual background at the top because they are afraid of seeming shallow. That instinct makes tutorials worse. Diátaxis argues that tutorials should minimize explanation during the lesson itself. Google makes a similar point in its tutorial material on sample code by pushing writers to focus comments on non-intuitive parts and to explain why near the code when that explanation is needed.
+
+I follow a simple rule: explanation earns its place only when it helps the reader execute the next action correctly. If a concept does not change the next decision, I either cut it or move it to a later explanation section or separate article.
+
+That rule fixes a common failure mode in infrastructure tutorials. A page on streaming responses does not need a mini-history of HTTP transport before the first request. A page on embeddings does not need a dense vector-space primer before the first API call. Readers need enough context to avoid cargo culting, but they do not need a seminar before they can print the first token or store the first vector.
+
+I used the same principle in my piece on [agent harnesses](/blog/agent-harnesses/). Readers can absorb checkpointing and execution loops because the article isolates those responsibilities clearly instead of trying to teach every agent design problem at once. Tutorial writing benefits from the same discipline.
+
+## Good tutorials remove choices early and reintroduce them later
+
+Choice looks generous to experts and hostile to beginners. Cognitive-load theory calls out another effect that matters here: [guidance fading and the expertise reversal effect](https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0963721420922183). Heavy guidance helps novices, then becomes redundant as expertise grows. A beginner needs one approved path. An experienced reader needs branching options.
+
+That is why I structure a tutorial in phases:
+
+| Phase | What I include | What I deliberately exclude |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| First run | Exact versions, exact commands, exact file contents, exact expected output | Alternatives, architecture digressions, optimization choices |
+| Second pass | Brief explanation of why the previous step worked | Edge cases that require new concepts |
+| After success | Links to how-to guides, references, migration notes, and production hardening | Anything that would have blocked the first success |
+
+Generic tutorials often invert that order. They present three databases, two deployment paths, four auth options, and a paragraph on tradeoffs before the reader has any concrete result. I think that is a category error. Options are useful after a reader has one working path to compare against.
+
+An honest limitation belongs here. Tight tutorials can annoy advanced readers who already know the basics and want direct comparisons. I do not solve that by bloating the tutorial. I solve it by publishing adjacent material. A tutorial teaches the first successful path. A how-to guide answers variant tasks. A reference page catalogs options. A changelog explains product movement over time, which is a separate writing job that I covered in my post on [writing changelogs developers actually read](/blog/how-to-write-a-changelog-developers-actually-read/).
+
+## Sample code is part of the pedagogy, not decoration
+
+Google's sample-code guide makes a point I wish more documentation teams took seriously: sample code should be treated like production code, tested continually, and maintained as systems change. That is not just a quality bar. That is a teaching requirement.
+
+Broken sample code teaches the wrong lesson. Hidden setup teaches the wrong lesson. Clever abstractions teach the wrong lesson when the reader cannot see the moving parts yet.
+
+I write tutorial code with a different standard from demo code:
+
+1. I choose names that expose meaning instead of compressing it.
+2. I keep helper layers shallow so readers can see cause and effect.
+3. I avoid copy that describes code the reader can already read.
+4. I comment the non-obvious choice or the safety tradeoff.
+5. I run every command from a fresh environment before I trust the draft.
+
+Fresh-environment testing matters more than writers admit. I have watched tutorials "pass" because the author had environment variables, global packages, seed data, and local credentials sitting around from earlier work. Readers inherit none of that state. A tutorial tested only on the author's laptop is not tested.
+
+GitHub's tutorial model also asks for [a link to the completed project](https://docs.github.com/en/contributing/style-guide-and-content-model/content-models/tutorials-and-quickstarts). I like that requirement because it gives the reader a diff target. They can compare their state against the known-good result instead of staring at a broken terminal and guessing which file drifted.
+
+## Teaching requires editorial sequencing, not just clean sentences
+
+Sentence-level clarity is table stakes. Strong tutorials also control sequence. Google's sample-code guidance recommends a range of complexity from a basic hello-world example to more advanced use cases. That sequencing maps cleanly to how novices acquire a skill. One working action comes first. Variation comes second. Transfer comes third.
+
+I usually draft tutorials in three passes:
+
+1. I write the happy path with every prerequisite and every visible check.
+2. I remove anything that does not change the next action.
+3. I add the minimum explanation needed for transfer, which means the reader can repeat the task without copying every line blindly.
+
+Transfer is the real test. A reader who finishes your tutorial and cannot adapt it from "upload one file" to "upload all files in a directory" did not learn much. Completion is easy to fake. Transfer is harder.
+
+One of the common briefs I get from DevTools teams asks for exactly that kind of transfer: teach a new concept fast enough for search traffic, but with enough depth that engineers can use the product after the article ends. That is the line I try to hold in my writing work, and my [work page](/work) shows the kinds of developer-facing pieces I write when a team needs that balance.
+
+## My checklist for a tutorial that teaches
+
+I use seven checks before I call a tutorial finished:
+
+1. One beginner skill sits at the center of the page.
+2. One clean environment defines the path.
+3. One finished artifact proves success.
+4. Every step has an observable result.
+5. Every command has real setup and real expected output.
+6. Every explanation earns its place by unlocking the next action.
+7. Every optional path waits until after the first successful run.
+
+A page that misses one of those checks can still be useful. A page that misses three usually turns into a support ticket generator.
+
+## FAQ
+
+**How long should a technical tutorial be?**
+
+I aim for the shortest length that can preserve setup, execution, checks, and one layer of explanation. Many good tutorials land between 1,200 and 2,500 words. Scope controls length more effectively than sentence trimming. If the draft keeps growing, I usually have a scope problem, not an editing problem.
+
+**Should I include architecture diagrams in a tutorial?**
+
+I include a diagram only when it changes a step the reader is about to take. A queue, webhook, or multi-service flow can benefit from one small diagram. Decorative system maps usually slow the lesson down. Readers need a runnable path first.
+
+**Should a tutorial cover multiple stacks or languages?**
+
+I strongly prefer one stack per tutorial. Multiple stacks multiply maintenance cost and force branch points into every section. Separate tutorials or separate code tabs can work later, once one path is stable and fully tested.
+
+**How much troubleshooting belongs in the main flow?**
+
+I include only the failure modes a beginner is likely to hit during the first run. Common auth errors, missing environment variables, dependency mismatches, and incorrect file paths belong in the body. Rare edge cases belong in a separate troubleshooting section or reference page.
+
+**What is the clearest sign that a tutorial is actually teaching?**
+
+I look for transfer. A reader should be able to change one meaningful variable after finishing and still succeed. If they can swap a model name, add one field, or point the workflow at a different file without restarting from zero, the tutorial probably taught a skill instead of staging a copy-paste performance.
