Technical tutorials often fail at the teaching part. They get a reader from blank project to demo output, then call it success even though the reader could not repeat the task from memory, explain the moving parts, or debug the first deviation from the happy path.

I think the root problem is simple: many teams publish product walkthroughs and label them tutorials. A tutorial is a lesson, not a tour. That distinction changes how I choose the starting state, the order of steps, the amount of explanation, and the kind of proof I expect from the reader at each checkpoint.

**Short answer:** I write tutorials as controlled learning environments. I define the learner, freeze the prerequisites, remove branching, show one meaningful decision at a time, and add checkpoints that prove understanding before the reader moves on. Frameworks like [Diataxis](https://diataxis.fr/tutorials-how-to/) and guidance from [Google's technical writing course](https://developers.google.com/tech-writing/one/documents) and [procedure style guide](https://developers.google.com/style/procedures) support that structure, but the hard part is editorial discipline.

## A tutorial teaches skill acquisition, not task completion

My take is that most teams misuse the word "tutorial." Diataxis draws a hard line between tutorials and how-to guides: tutorials serve a user who is at study, while how-to guides serve a user who is at work ([Diataxis](https://diataxis.fr/tutorials-how-to/)). That sounds academic until you edit real docs. Once I start treating a tutorial as a lesson for someone acquiring competence, weak drafts become obvious fast.

Product teams often hand me a brief that says "write a tutorial for feature X." What they usually want is "show users how to turn feature X on." That can be valuable, but it is usually a setup guide or a task guide. A teaching tutorial has a narrower job. It should leave the reader with one transferable mental model and one repeatable skill.

I have seen this go wrong in a very specific way. A draft opens with a few paragraphs of concept explanation, then throws the reader into a terminal block with eight commands, three environment variables, and two unstated prerequisites. The reader can still reach the final screenshot if everything works. The learning fails because the draft asks for execution before orientation.

The non-obvious editorial move is to cut scope until the learning objective becomes testable. Google tells writers to define scope, non-scope, audience, and what readers should know or do after reading ([Google Technical Writing](https://developers.google.com/tech-writing/one/documents)). Tutorials need that discipline more than reference docs do. If I cannot write a one-sentence answer to "what new competence will the reader have after step 7," I am not ready to draft.

## A good tutorial starts by freezing the learner's starting state

Readers do not arrive as abstract "developers." They arrive with a machine, a shell, a browser, a level of context, and a short tolerance for ambiguity. Good tutorials reduce uncertainty before the first action.

Google's documentation course says a document should state audience and prerequisite knowledge explicitly ([Google Technical Writing](https://developers.google.com/tech-writing/one/documents)). The Carpentries training material pushes the same idea from a teaching angle: novices often do not know what questions to ask yet, which means the lesson has to carry more of the navigation burden ([The Carpentries Instructor Training](https://preview.carpentries.org/instructor-training/instructor/aio.html)).

That is why I front-load four things in every serious tutorial:

1. The exact reader profile.
2. The exact environment.
3. The exact success state.
4. The exact non-scope.

That sounds obvious. Hardly anyone does it rigorously. "Basic knowledge of Docker is recommended" is not enough. I would rather write "I assume you can run `docker compose up`, read container logs, and edit a YAML file without extra guidance." Readers can self-select with that. Editorial teams also get a sharper review target.

Non-scope matters just as much. Google makes the point directly: scope and non-scope help both the reader and the writer stay aligned ([Google Technical Writing](https://developers.google.com/tech-writing/one/documents)). A tutorial should say what it will not teach. Maybe I will teach how to add prompt caching to an API workflow, but I will not teach prompt engineering from scratch. Maybe I will teach how to wire a tracing SDK, but I will not cover production alerting. That line protects the learning path from detours.

## Step order should follow the learner's decisions, not the product architecture

Engineering teams usually explain systems by component: API, SDK, worker, queue, UI, storage. Learners experience systems by decision: install, configure, run, inspect, fix, repeat. Those are not the same sequence.

Google's procedure guidance is useful here because it forces writers to think in execution order. Steps should state the goal before the action, specify the context before the click or command, and focus on one reader decision at a time ([Google developer documentation style guide](https://developers.google.com/style/procedures)). That sounds small. That choice changes comprehension.

I learned this the hard way writing infrastructure tutorials. Early drafts often mirrored the system design because I had the architecture in my head. Readers did not. A section called "Configure the background worker" made sense to me because I knew the worker existed and why it mattered. A novice needed "Send the job to a queue so the request can return immediately" before they needed implementation detail. Once I rewrote sections around the reader's next decision, completion rates in review improved and review comments shifted from "I got lost" to "step 5 needs one more example."

Good tutorial sequencing usually follows a pattern like this:

1. Establish the goal in concrete terms.
2. Create the minimal working setup.
3. Run the first visible success case.
4. Explain the one concept that makes that success legible.
5. Modify one variable and observe the change.
6. Add one failure case and recover from it.

That fifth and sixth step are where a tutorial starts teaching instead of escorting. A reader who changes one parameter and predicts the result is learning. A reader who sees one controlled failure and fixes it is building a mental model.

## Worked examples beat open-ended problem solving for novices

Educational research backs up something many strong tutorial writers discover by instinct: novices need well-designed examples before they need improvisation. A 2025 paper in *ACM Transactions on Computing Education* studied 75 university students in their first programming course and found that worked examples reduced extraneous cognitive load and improved retention; guided self-explanations also helped transfer learning ([ACM TOCE paper](https://dl.acm.org/doi/full/10.1145/3732791)).

That matters for tutorial writing because many drafts expect readers to solve too much too early. A writer might say, "Now adapt the code to your use case." That is a lazy handoff, not a teaching move. A better tutorial gives the reader a worked example, then asks for one bounded adaptation with a reason for making it.

I treat worked examples as a design rule:

1. Show the whole thing once.
2. Label why each piece exists.
3. Ask the reader to change one thing.
4. Ask the reader to explain what changed and why.

Carpentries takes a similar stance in practice. Their instructor training emphasizes hands-on practice, immediate feedback, and building mental models through specific problems with specific tools rather than abstract lectures ([The Carpentries Instructor Training](https://preview.carpentries.org/instructor-training/instructor/aio.html)). That is exactly how strong technical tutorials should behave.

Readers also need checkpoints that verify state, not just progress. "You should now see output similar to..." is better than nothing. Stronger tutorials tell the reader what conclusion to draw from the output. If the app returns `cache_hit: true`, I want to say what that proves. If a trace shows two spans instead of one, I want to say what changed in execution. A checkpoint without interpretation is just screenshot choreography.

## Explanation belongs after contact with the system

I dislike tutorials that open with 600 words of background. Readers have not earned any of that context yet. They have no hooks for it.

MDN's technical writing guidance recommends a logical progression from foundational concepts into examples and stresses one idea per sentence and one main idea per paragraph ([MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/blog/technical-writing/)). MDN also suggests aiming for 15 to 20 words per sentence. I would not turn that into a law, but I do use it as a warning sign during self-edit. Dense explanation before the first successful action usually means I am writing for myself, not for a learner.

My preferred pattern is setup, first success, then explanation. A reader runs something, sees a result, and only then gets the abstraction that makes the result useful. That order gives the concept somewhere to land.

Good explanations inside tutorials also stay close to the artifact on screen. If the step creates a `docker-compose.yml`, I explain the two fields the reader just touched and ignore the ones they do not need yet. If the step adds a tracing middleware, I explain where the span begins and ends, not the full history of observability. Restraint is what keeps a tutorial from collapsing into reference documentation.

## Strong tutorials remove branches until the reader has earned them

One of Google's sharper recommendations is to document one best way when there is more than one way to complete a task ([Google developer documentation style guide](https://developers.google.com/style/procedures)). I think that advice is even more important for tutorials than for procedures. Branching explodes cognitive load.

